utton issues. It has stared down France on the issue of Muslim immigration; Ireland on abortion; Greece on Greek Orthodoxy; Turkey on Kurdish separatism; Austria on Nazism; and Britain on gay rights and corporal punishment. And what is most extraordinary is that nations commonly comply. In the battle for the world’s conscience, Goldhaber shows how the court in Strasbourg may be pulling ahead.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aConstitutional lawzEurope. 0aEuropean Court of Human RightsxHistory. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  apolitical science, law, human rights, history, world history, criminology, criminal justice, supreme court, scotus, public rights, european court of human rights, echr, ecthr, international court, european convention on human rights, supreme court of europe, france, europe, court, council of europe, immigration, muslim immigration, abortion, greek orthodoxy, kurdish separatism, nazism, gay rights, corporal punishment, ireland, turkey, austria, britain, legal, judicial, lawyer, european union, human rights protection.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831106886100 cprintz978081353983640uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081354128040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813541280423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813541280/original  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK